    • Choose "I'll use GoDaddy nameservers"

    • Save

If you used CNAME or A records to connect to Wix instead, just remove those from the DNS record section.

✅ STEP 2: Set Up Your GitHub Website (If Not Done Yet)

Let me know and I’ll give you the exact .zip folder with a simple index.html file — all you’ll have to do is:

  1. Create a GitHub repo named: yourusername.github.io

  2. Upload the contents of the zip (just the index.html)

  3. Done — your site will be live at: https://yourusername.github.io

✅ STEP 3: Connect Your Domain from GoDaddy to GitHub Pages

On GitHub:

  1. Go to your repo → Settings → Scroll to Pages

  2. Under "Custom Domain", type your domain (e.g., www.yourname.com) and click Save

GitHub will try to automatically create a CNAME file — if it doesn’t, you can do it manually.

On GoDaddy:

  1. In GoDaddy → DNS settings for your domain

  2. Add or modify these records:

TypeNameValue
A@185.199.108.153
A@185.199.109.153
A@185.199.110.153
A@185.199.111.153
CNAMEwwwyourusername.github.io. (include the period at end)

These are GitHub’s official IPs for custom domains.

  1. Save changes

✅ STEP 4: Wait for It to Go Live

DNS changes usually take 10 minutes to a few hours. When it’s ready, you’ll see your GitHub-hosted page on your custom domain.

  4. Save it exactly as:

  5. Set Save as type to:

    • "All Files" (on Windows)
